g stations, which alleviates some range anxiety.3  Interestingly, hybrids seem to be making inroads and are becoming an alternative of choice for OEMs and consumers.4 But the death of internal combustion (IC) vehicles seems to have been greatly exaggerated, as they will still be on the road for years to come.5  Emerging Technology Vehicles are evolving from mere means of transportation to fully connected devices. This transformation is prompting a shift in the overall vehicle experience, as manufacturers increasingly incorporate comprehensive software suites to facilitate integration with other smart devices. This digital shift is fostering personalized user experiences, enabling over-the-air updates, and leading to the development of more sophisticated infotainment systems. However, as vehicles become more connected, the risk of data breaches and cyberattacks rises. Vehicle cyberthreats remain a significant concern for consumer cybersecurity6, necessitating that dealers offer robust training and comprehensive protection solutions to safeguard customers. The demand for personalized experiences extends to the car-buying process as well. In the post-pandemic era, there has been a noticeable shift towards digital tools in automotive retail. Today, 59% of car buyers prefer using digital tools provided by dealerships7, which facilitate various aspects of the buying process, including financing options, vehicle browsing, and educational resources to aid decision-making. Supply Chain Disruptions The pandemic unleashed widespread supply chain disruptions, from which the automotive industry is still recovering. The United Auto Workers (UAW) strike and ongoing semiconductor chip shortage brought more headwinds, resulting in a volatile market. Supply chain disruptions have broad-reaching implications, affecting dealerships and consumers alike. They lead to inventory shortages and drive-up vehicle prices.8 Between 2020 and 2021, the price of new cars surged by 17.2%.9 While vehicle prices are beginning to stabilize as inventory levels recover, dealerships must remain vigilant and prepared to adapt to potential operational changes. The Takeaway While data and trends can provide insights into what 2024 may hold, it is impossible to predict the future with certainty. The automotive industry is subject to rapid changes driven by technological advancements, regulatory shifts, market demands, interest rates and global events. The past has shown that the world can change in an instant, underscoring the importance of resilience and staying well-informed as the automotive industry navigates the uncertainties of the coming year. 1Global EV Outlook, IEA 2“How Americans view electric vehicles,” Pew Research 3“The Number of Electric Vehicle Charging Ports in the U.S. Nearly Doubled in the Past Three Years,” Department of Energy 4“Gas-electric hybrid vehicles get a boost in the US from Ford, other,” Reuters 5“Stellantis sees long road ahead for internal combustion engine cars,” Reuters 6Global Cyber Security 2023 Study, CMS 7Buying Outlook, Capital One 8“Autoworkers’ Strike Could Affect New Car Prices,” Consumer Reports 9“Average car price is at an all-time high of $47,000 going into 2022,” The Zebra Letter to the Editor Send us a letter Have an opinion about this story? Click here to submit a Letter to the Editor, and we may publish it in print.  Sign up for free newsletters   Daily Summary (weekdays)  Weekly Summary (Mondays)  Breaking News Alerts (as needed)  Yes, I'd like to receive email communications on editorial features, special offers, research and events and webinars from Automotive News.  EMAIL ADDRESS Please enter a valid email address. Please enter your email address. Please verify captcha. Please select at least one newsletter to subscribe. See more newsletter options at autonews.com/newsletters. You can unsubscribe at any time through links in these emails. For more information, see our Privacy Policy. Digital Edition THIS WEEK'S EDITIO